@gougouzcm

Thank you for your suggestions, I have an idea that if dubbo-admin supports dynamic modification of client parameters and automatic refer, it can solve all the dynamic call problems.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15549777/38911808-407fffbe-4304-11e8-8272-b280d9661e15.png)

@beiwei30 

Sorry, dubbo doesn't support this feature yet. I hope dubbo team can consider this feature.

Thanks for your report. I have got some questions:

1. What do you exactly mean by `The recent version of ValidationFilter has been upgrade to return RpcResult, but it seems not completely.`? I don't fully understand.
```java
} catch (Throwable t) {
      return new RpcResult(t);
}
```

2. I don't think `new RpcResult(new RpcException(new ConstraintViolationException(set)));` is a good practice, mixing RpcResult with RpcException.

3. 
> But failed with ConstraintDescriptorImpl deserialization with some error likes "ConstraintDescriptorImpl could not be instantiated."

Isn't this caused by dependency absent or version mismatch? At least, i don't understand the difference of extending ConstraintViolationException with a customized class.

I think you should look at this `LOCK` as a whole, we have null check before entering this lock:
```java
Monitor monitor = MONITORS.get(key);
        Future<Monitor> future = FUTURES.get(key);
        if (monitor != null || future != null) {
            return monitor;
        }

        LOCK.lock();
        try {
            monitor = MONITORS.get(key);
            future = FUTURES.get(key);
            if (monitor != null || future != null) {
                return monitor;
            }

            final URL monitorUrl = url;
            final ListenableFutureTask<Monitor> listenableFutureTask = ListenableFutureTask.create(new MonitorCreator(monitorUrl));
            listenableFutureTask.addListener(new MonitorListener(key));
            executor.execute(listenableFutureTask);
            FUTURES.put(key, listenableFutureTask);

            return null;
        } finally {
            // unlock
            LOCK.unlock();
        }
```
